1 ContributorIs Music Really Haram? The Sad Reality of Today‚Äôs Music. LyricsIs Music Really Haram?
It‚Äôs the question almost everyone wants to argue about and the debate that never seems to end.
And before you drop the ‚ÄúHaram Police‚Äù card and get ready to prepare an essay response in the comments, can I just say that I‚Äôm not here to argue the different rulings and opinions on musical instruments, singing, beat boxing, drums and what not. I‚Äôm not even going to go there.
I‚Äôm going to be doing something different.
I want us to answer this question for ourselves, openly and honestly. In fact, we can even forget I even said the word Haram to begin with.
Let‚Äôs instead just ask the question ‚ÄúIs Music harmful?‚Äù
And when we say music, I‚Äôm going to be very blank, I‚Äôm referring to the music that the majority of people are listening to today because that‚Äôs what we should be concerned about. The music that‚Äôs on our radios, TV‚Äôs, phones and iTunes playlists on repeat. The songs that are topping the charts week-in-week-out and have us memorizing their lyrics from A-Z. This is the music I‚Äôm referring to.
Should we, as Muslims be fine listening to this stuff?

No, no I won‚Äôt tell nobody‚Äù
‚ÄúIf you want drama, Grab the Uzi‚Äù.

A quick Google search of the lyrics of these songs will let you know exactly the kinds of messages they contain. You honestly don‚Äôt have to read far until you come across references to drugs, sexual promiscuity, violence or alcohol. Even when lyrics can seem somewhat innocent, they are underlined with the most vulgar and shameless of meanings. And the saddest part of it all, there‚Äôs even some Muslims actually making these songs.
And yes, I‚Äôm sure we can argue all day that not all songs are this bad and there are some ‚Äúgood songs‚Äù out there, but the fact of the matter is the statistics speak for themselves when they mention that the vast majority of today‚Äôs music is riddled with such references and as the day‚Äôs go by content is only getting worse.
And as I‚Äôve mentioned before, I‚Äôm not here to argue the Islamic rulings on instruments and the various opinions of scholars on music, because, in all honesty, these opinions are irrelevant when we consider them in light of the music being listened to today. And we can go ahead and argue that we‚Äôre strong and that the music isn‚Äôt necessarily influencing us, but the fact of the matter is ‚Äì it does. And whether you realize it or not, when you constantly grant such music free access to your ears, it is affecting you. And if you were so sure that the things you listen to won‚Äôt affect your life, why not switch up a music playlist with some Quran and see what change it would have in your life. Even if you don‚Äôt understand a word being recited, just listen to it and see what kind of impact it will leave on your soul. There‚Äôs no denying that our ears are gateways into our hearts and we should be very careful who we allow access to.
